AI/ML Model Research
Development of Interactive Cyber Threat Visualization Dashboard
Introduction
The objective of this document is to research and analyze different Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning models relevant to the Development of an Interactive Cyber Threat Visualization Dashboard. A total of 10 AI/ML models have been studied and compared based on their working principles, accuracy, advantages, disadvantages, and real-world applications. Based on this research, the most suitable model for the project has been selected.

Model 1: Linear Regression
Type: Supervised Learning
Used For: Prediction and regression problems

Description:
Linear Regression establishes a linear relationship between input features and output variables.

Accuracy:
Provides good accuracy for simple and linear datasets.

Advantages:

Easy to implement
Fast execution
Disadvantages:

Not suitable for complex data
Applications:
Trend analysis, forecasting

Model 2: Logistic Regression
Type: Supervised Learning
Used For: Binary classification

Description:
Logistic Regression uses a sigmoid function to classify data into binary classes.

Accuracy:
High accuracy for linearly separable data.

Advantages:

Efficient and simple
Interpretable results
Disadvantages:

Performs poorly with non-linear data
Applications:
Malware detection, intrusion detection

Model 3: Decision Tree
Type: Supervised Learning
Used For: Classification and regression

Description:
Decision Tree splits data into branches based on conditions.

Accuracy:
Moderate to high depending on depth.

Advantages:

Easy to visualize
Handles non-linear data
Disadvantages:

Prone to overfitting
Applications:
Attack classification, threat analysis

Model 4: Random Forest
Type: Supervised Learning
Used For: Classification and regression

Description:
Random Forest combines multiple decision trees to improve prediction accuracy.

Accuracy:
High accuracy with reduced overfitting.

Advantages:

Robust and stable
Handles large datasets well
Disadvantages:

High computational cost
Applications:
Cyber attack detection, anomaly detection

Model 5: Support Vector Machine (SVM)
Type: Supervised Learning
Used For: Classification

Description:
SVM finds the optimal hyperplane separating different classes.

Accuracy:
High accuracy for high-dimensional data.

Advantages:

Effective for complex data
Disadvantages:

Slow for very large datasets
Applications:
Intrusion detection systems

Model 6: K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
Type: Supervised Learning
Used For: Classification

Description:
KNN classifies data based on similarity to nearest data points.

Accuracy:
Good accuracy for small datasets.

Advantages:

Simple and intuitive
Disadvantages:

High memory usage
Applications:
Pattern recognition in network traffic

Model 7: Naive Bayes
Type: Supervised Learning
Used For: Classification

Description:
Naive Bayes is based on probability and Bayesâ€™ theorem.

Accuracy:
High accuracy for text-based and log data.

Advantages:

Fast and scalable
Disadvantages:

Assumes feature independence
Applications:
Spam detection, log classification

Model 8: Gradient Boosting (XGBoost)
Type: Supervised Learning
Used For: Classification and regression

Description:
XGBoost builds models sequentially to reduce previous errors.

Accuracy:
Very high accuracy.

Advantages:

Excellent performance
Handles complex patterns
Disadvantages:

Complex tuning
Applications:
Advanced threat prediction

Model 9: Artificial Neural Network (ANN)
Type: Deep Learning
Used For: Pattern recognition

Description:
ANN mimics the human brain using layers of neurons.

Accuracy:
High accuracy with sufficient training data.

Advantages:

Learns complex relationships
Disadvantages:

Requires large datasets
Applications:
Cyber threat classification

Model 10: LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory)
Type: Deep Learning
Used For: Time-series analysis

Description:
LSTM is designed to handle sequential and temporal data.

Accuracy:
High accuracy for time-based data.

Advantages:

Captures long-term dependencies
Disadvantages:

Computationally expensive
Applications:
Real-time cyber attack prediction

Model Comparison
Traditional models are simpler but limited in handling complex cyber data. Tree-based and ensemble models perform better for structured attack datasets. Deep learning models provide high accuracy for large-scale and real-time cyber threat analysis but require more resources.

Selected Model
Random Forest is selected as the most suitable model for this project.

Reason for Selection
Random Forest offers high accuracy, reduces overfitting, and efficiently handles complex and high-dimensional cyber security datasets. It is reliable for detecting anomalies and classifying cyber threats.

Application in the Project
In this project, the Random Forest model will be trained using historical cyber threat data. The model will analyze network traffic patterns and detect potential cyber attacks. The predictions will be visualized through an interactive dashboard to support real-time monitoring and decision-making.

Conclusion
This research analyzed 10 AI/ML models for cyber threat visualization. Based on performance and suitability, Random Forest was selected as the best model for the project.
